Ns2RCo7KPJShdSmg_eG7vnq4bmMSkpS3xxZAtrup5JDu43S_QLaxDqfIJLWQS8fcSpIFdkCHPCKKx4vwKdJfZQRqW9HIIBnTF74PaYcOEHqHWe6D2jVJBG_BRRPnKfKoz_BguJEwND65HgqpyMWX2SykroJHGwqd2wTOensUqG5nFfncj3t4kn9aEyTRyuayJOKMM9K1xyP-fHfKTinNHIrNSEiCdCdlB_8HShvz8MnfrEADenxyalNBsW3Hb688d6oIWWBjFquQsXeFmvgEHRMfCfyV-jDzjXskoo5Kc6L4uwyoOjtjviDDDumGA0vJ3Q1E1E4bfMSlhOFzO6gSSSJNXrPADx23x9RCfoMfsNUcQMGEACVQjrpbAAYU9qryBO6kU12kSKxaZx11z228zby4ghmY-RdEVicFzJRl7GzzEOp3ABhNkZHIlJwSYaXcf_1yn-lv8Qth7AaZ5VXDjyaAMQt9XnSbUY-F2H8j8ggtahb2U_oaDgXptiiqxp4HB5VUE_FPVCj411WUywQw07cwVaE7RLpqI7orooMrfY-JEwjE5JW2isgwvXBS1K4RtqKsG_B4EVqEDGcaFvFQmWeF5aQzwuK5_22xwmpNuim91eC7sTt7rk9tAWRJZHcm_Iyp-UcSkI6AtoOextn4fcMCd2nSP2Yr2XAXH_Iu4MW79_KgJghkaKnj8gIZmRtgPNobUVDfOqSeVcbNOVpeRcOABkbdBCU99wHZr4lnqv6EMuO3QMqxp_DdNliqG4430fwQmpuiqFCGQcbfIHM-4Ja2oWydckHHCHyOjWPpTg0xLnsvcdkIQNPITdc1Xe1c8_FZEZ9ZkcvLYphVW7k1GrsmdMEbVpfnBiA==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating library coverage**\\n\\nI'm considering how to provide meaningful coverage of library integration, particularly with Hibernate and Ehcache. Normally, Hibernate's second-level cache is standard, but it looks like we’re facing issues because the POM file only declares hibernate-core as provided. Current tests don't seem to include Hibernate, and it appears to be a run failure rather than an issue with the library itself. For meaningful coverage, I think we only need basic testing with CacheManager, Cache, and Element without unnecessary complexities.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering update checks**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how the system may perform an update check. The configuration can be adjusted to set updateCheck=false to avoid this, which is something that should ideally be part of the generated tests. I’m wondering if this setup goes beyond what’s expected in the standard scaffold. It seems like there's guidance to set this system property, as existing tests consistently skip the update check to ensure no network calls are made.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering build dependencies**\\n\\nThe task is about representing dependencies that a driver can use before generating something. The existing build has those dependencies, but the new worktree for version 2.5.0 might not include them. For a workflow that's updating from version 2.4.4 to 2.5.0, I wonder if the driver could just copy the existing build. Hmm, it seems like a possible solution, but I need to think about the implications of doing that.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Validating system configurations**\\n\\nI’m considering that BTM or old JTA might be outdated and would benefit from native metadata updates. It seems like the local Gradle/native image is the current authoritative version. If the config has updateCheck disabled, then the system property could be unnecessary. I need to make sure that the final output is valid JSON and can include an object. Perhaps I'll also mention a brief research summary.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n  \"summary\": \"Ehcache core is usable in-process without Docker, but meaningful coverage of its documented XA/JTA transaction path needs provided/optional transaction APIs that the artifact does not bring transitively; tests should also disable Ehcache update checks.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"dependency\",\n      \"coordinate\": \"javax.transaction:jta:1.1\",\n      \"scope\": \"testImplementation\",\n      \"reason\": \"ehcache-core 2.5.0 declares JTA as provided, while its transaction APIs and XA helpers expose javax.transaction types; Java 25 does not provide these classes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"dependency\",\n      \"coordinate\": \"org.codehaus.btm:btm:2.1.4\",\n      \"scope\": \"testImplementation\",\n      \"reason\": \"Ehcache documentation describes third-party transaction managers such as Bitronix for global transactions, and DefaultTransactionManagerLookup coverage needs an actual TransactionManager implementation outside an application server.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"dependency\",\n      \"coordinate\": \"org.apache.geronimo.specs:geronimo-jms_1.1_spec:1.1.1\",\n      \"scope\": \"testImplementation\",\n      \"reason\": \"Bitronix declares the JMS 1.1 API as optional; adding the spec avoids class-loading gaps when Bitronix resource/transaction-manager classes are initialized during JVM or native tests.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"Disable Ehcache's update checker in generated tests, preferably before creating any CacheManager: set System.setProperty(\\\"net.sf.ehcache.skipUpdateCheck\\\", \\\"true\\\") or configure updateCheck(false). Use temporary directories for diskStore paths and always shut down CacheManager instances. Avoid Terracotta/clustered-cache tests unless a separate server setup is intentionally added.\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"ehcache-core also contains optional Terracotta, Hibernate, servlet, and sizeof-agent integration points; these are not required for core in-process coverage and should not be exercised accidentally without additional setup.\",\n    \"Bitronix and JTA 1.1 are old dependencies, so local Gradle and Native Image verification remain authoritative for whether their metadata is sufficient.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_06f3724d7bda919f016a42de7552a88196801020cbbb9b8048\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2270, "output": 1846, "cacheRead": 31744, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 35860, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1782767197900, "responseId": "resp_06f3724d7bda919f016a42de5e7b9081968541c415c2c276b5"}, "toolResults": []}
